1
00:00:03,186 --> 00:00:28,384
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:29,039 --> 00:00:33,243
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,905 --> 00:00:57,831
I thought this evening we'd have a look at the sort of ground upon which the Buddha builds the whole architecture of his teaching, the word dukkha, and then to look at the five khandhas, which is really a deconstruction of our person, our personhood.

4
00:00:58,957 --> 00:01:02,542
And then just see what we mean by karma from that point of view.

5
00:01:04,165 --> 00:01:11,956
So this word dukkha, the root meaning is two words, du and ka.

6
00:01:12,115 --> 00:01:16,042
Du just means hard and ka means to bear, hard to bear.

7
00:01:16,722 --> 00:01:22,631
And it's variously translated as, you know, suffering, unsatisfactoriness, etc.

8
00:01:23,792 --> 00:01:24,173
But

9
00:01:25,250 --> 00:01:33,459
This doesn't just simply include, you know, those things that are obvious suffering like physical pain.

10
00:01:34,180 --> 00:01:36,462
That's pretty straightforward, physical pain.

11
00:01:37,343 --> 00:01:39,167
But it also includes pleasure.

12
00:01:40,128 --> 00:01:52,201
Pleasures are pleasant while we're enjoying them, but the problem is they're transient and therefore they never actually, you know, produce what we want, which is

13
00:01:52,435 --> 00:01:56,881
I mean, what we're trying to head for is a continuous and perfect happiness.

14
00:01:57,042 --> 00:01:59,504
I mean, that's the definition of nirvana.

15
00:02:00,966 --> 00:02:07,837
But it's not quite an emotional happiness, but we'll come to that, hopefully, in the fullness of time.

16
00:02:07,876 --> 00:02:21,497
So this word dukkha includes all our physical problems, all our mental sufferings, our emotional problems,

17
00:02:21,983 --> 00:02:27,868
But it also includes all the delightful side of life because it disappears.

18
00:02:28,930 --> 00:02:36,739
And at base, it includes this existential angst, all this business around sickness, aging, and death.

19
00:02:37,139 --> 00:02:45,247
So in a sense, dukkha is a view of life as basically unsatisfactory.

20
00:02:46,209 --> 00:02:51,213
And that in itself isn't a problem.

21
00:02:51,581 --> 00:02:52,783
That's the thing.

22
00:02:52,903 --> 00:03:00,433
The actual sufferings of life and the joys of life and sickness, aging and death are in themselves not the problem.

23
00:03:00,854 --> 00:03:03,237
The problem is how we relate to them.

24
00:03:03,859 --> 00:03:10,568
And this is the problem of attachment, indulgence, wrong view.

25
00:03:11,650 --> 00:03:15,615
And this roots itself in this whole idea of a self.

26
00:03:16,961 --> 00:03:21,268
So if we just for a minute stop with this business of a self.

27
00:03:21,407 --> 00:03:23,009
Now, what do we actually mean there, you see?

28
00:03:24,050 --> 00:03:36,167
What the Buddha is proposing is that there is something in us which doesn't belong to this psychophysical organism and we'll deconstruct that as he does it in a minute.

29
00:03:37,788 --> 00:03:46,479
He says there's something in us which is not that and the discovery eventually, of course, is that it's none other than this very awareness.

30
00:03:47,100 --> 00:03:56,675
Now, the image I use, or should we say the myth I use, to sort of give us an idea as to what's happening is the myth of Narcissus.

31
00:03:57,616 --> 00:04:03,564
So remember, Narcissus looks into this pond and he sees this beautiful youth and he falls in love with it.

32
00:04:04,385 --> 00:04:09,813
And that draws him into an embrace of this figure in the pond.

33
00:04:10,133 --> 00:04:11,556
And of course, he drowns.

34
00:04:12,143 --> 00:04:20,932
So water is always, not always, but mostly in mythology, something that's creative.

35
00:04:21,934 --> 00:04:39,213
And so if we think of the mind, the heart mind, the body heart mind, this whole organism as a pond, the awareness is looking into it, you see, and it looks into it and it has that feeling of presence.

36
00:04:39,937 --> 00:04:47,105
So when you're in a very quiet moment and you're just with yourself and you just get that sense of just presence, right?

37
00:04:47,125 --> 00:04:48,887
It's not the self of embarrassment.

38
00:04:49,827 --> 00:04:51,790
It's not the self of trying to get something.

39
00:04:51,850 --> 00:04:55,714
It's just that sense of being, that sense of presence.

40
00:04:55,735 --> 00:05:00,180
That is our first construction, right?

41
00:05:00,199 --> 00:05:07,327
And it's through that that we enter into the world that's being created by this psychophysical organism.

42
00:05:08,050 --> 00:05:17,778
So what we're doing in meditation is we're pulling ourselves out of that pond and sitting up back onto the bank of that pond.

43
00:05:19,120 --> 00:05:26,307
And when we do that, we get that sense of being the knower, the feeler, the one who is experiencing.

44
00:05:26,927 --> 00:05:33,473
And everything that's happening is happening on that screen, okay?

45
00:05:33,915 --> 00:05:36,437
You might say the surface of the pond.

46
00:05:36,889 --> 00:05:40,254
But of course you can see through the pond into the pond.

47
00:05:40,595 --> 00:06:06,492
So this consciousness that we have is multi-dimensional and it contains everything that we experience both at a physical level and a heart emotional mood level and at the intellectual level the imaginary level everything is it has to manifest on that surface, right and that's that's the the candor the the

48
00:06:06,978 --> 00:06:08,980
the aggregate of consciousness.

49
00:06:10,903 --> 00:06:18,634
Now, these consciousnesses are arising and passing away because they can only hold one sense base.

50
00:06:18,654 --> 00:06:35,819
So if you're watching a film on the telly and you're having a biscuit and a cup of tea or something, and you're hearing what's happening, you're seeing what's happening, we get that impression that it's all happening at the same time.

51
00:06:36,391 --> 00:06:47,387
But actually, in Buddhist psychology, these are all minute, infinitesimal little consciousnesses that run one after the other and give us the impression of wholeness.

52
00:06:48,988 --> 00:06:55,117
And that's really seeing impermanence at the level of how we create the world we experience.

53
00:06:56,600 --> 00:07:00,264
And that's all based upon this psychophysical organism.

54
00:07:00,966 --> 00:07:02,348
So...

55
00:07:03,120 --> 00:07:28,132
If we understand that when we are pulling ourselves back onto that observation post within ourselves, and we're observing and feeling and knowing, you know, physical stuff that comes up, emotional stuff, and even mental stuff, then we've already pulled out of that delusion of being this organism.

56
00:07:29,113 --> 00:07:32,317
Now, in order to reinforce that,

57
00:07:32,533 --> 00:07:45,754
the Buddha then, as it were, begins to deconstruct this very organism, and he splits it up into these aggregates, heaps, right?

58
00:07:45,774 --> 00:07:46,995
And the first one is the body.

59
00:07:47,557 --> 00:08:01,478
Now, it's a very strange situation we're in, because I definitely feel myself to be in the body, and often when I'm enjoying something, or when I'm

60
00:08:01,930 --> 00:08:07,976
When I've got a headache or whatever, I definitely am the body, right?

61
00:08:07,997 --> 00:08:12,661
And yet, when I question myself and ask, well, what is it I know of the body?

62
00:08:13,283 --> 00:08:15,565
It's an infinitesimal amount.

63
00:08:17,408 --> 00:08:21,552
For instance, at this present moment, our toenails are growing.

64
00:08:22,392 --> 00:08:24,315
Have you any idea that that's happening?

65
00:08:25,516 --> 00:08:30,822
It's only when you look down every so often and you think, well, I've got to cut those toenails, right?

66
00:08:31,192 --> 00:08:34,053
we never actually experience a toenail growing.

67
00:08:34,955 --> 00:08:43,982
And I've got this book on biology, which every page sort of has some detail in it, which is quite amazing.

68
00:08:44,043 --> 00:08:47,785
I mean, it's beyond acceptance in a way.

69
00:08:48,326 --> 00:08:56,313
For instance, I picked up this little bit of fact, the brain has 12, I mean, you might know this, of course, but for me, it's a bit shocking.

70
00:08:56,333 --> 00:09:01,197
The brain has 12 billion neurons and 50

71
00:09:01,346 --> 00:09:03,408
billions supporting glial cells.

72
00:09:03,850 --> 00:09:07,553
Now, I haven't a clue what a glial cell is, but there's 50 billion of them.

73
00:09:08,335 --> 00:09:09,655
And they're all up here in my head.

74
00:09:10,076 --> 00:09:11,597
At least I think I've got that amount.

75
00:09:11,759 --> 00:09:12,720
I might have a bit less.

76
00:09:14,562 --> 00:09:25,113
But even so, there are billions, not thousands, you know, not millions, billions, 12 billion neurons and 15 billion supporting glial cells.

77
00:09:25,133 --> 00:09:31,000
And the fact is that, you know, if I hadn't read that book, I basically wouldn't know that.

78
00:09:31,368 --> 00:09:34,571
I've no experience of a single neuron.

79
00:09:35,351 --> 00:09:39,756
And that shows you how ignorant I am of how my brain works, but it works.

80
00:09:39,996 --> 00:09:43,961
I mean, you know, generally speaking, I'm sort of fairly happy with it.

81
00:09:45,743 --> 00:09:48,806
I could wish it to be just a little bit more quick, but there we are.

82
00:09:49,667 --> 00:09:54,052
So wherever you look at the body, what you find are these cells.

83
00:09:54,091 --> 00:10:00,278
What they say is there are trillions of cells that make up the body and they're all,

84
00:10:00,595 --> 00:10:04,539
you know, dying, they're dying and then they're replacing.

85
00:10:04,561 --> 00:10:11,811
And they tell you that every seven years you've got a new body, but not for an instant have I felt anything dying as such.

86
00:10:12,672 --> 00:10:14,794
And yet this is what I'm told that's happening.

87
00:10:15,556 --> 00:10:28,594
So there's a sort of a disconnect between my experience of the body as something that I feel I'm in, I'm of, I feel it, I can move it around, wave my hands about.

88
00:10:28,777 --> 00:10:37,509
and yet the body itself has its own agenda, and its own agenda which I have no control over.

89
00:10:37,788 --> 00:10:46,561
Obviously the most shocking one is growing old and dropping dead, which is not something I'm particularly looking forward to.

90
00:10:47,022 --> 00:10:56,134
So you can see that when you actually contemplate the relationship we have with the body, it's very minimal, very minimal.

91
00:10:56,602 --> 00:10:59,027
and it's all dependent upon our senses.

92
00:11:00,428 --> 00:11:19,557
So these five physical senses give us information and it's from this information that we construct the world that we're experiencing, the outer world at least, and of course some of the inner world, the pain, the pleasures, etc.

93
00:11:20,633 --> 00:11:30,583
If we then ask, well, what is it that we're actually experiencing right down there at that physical base?

94
00:11:31,443 --> 00:11:33,907
The Buddha points to these four great elements.

95
00:11:34,768 --> 00:11:36,590
And that's what they're called, the four great elements.

96
00:11:37,831 --> 00:11:43,136
And this includes, I'm sure you know them, earth, water, fire, and air.

97
00:11:43,616 --> 00:11:49,003
And what they're referring to are specific types of sensations.

98
00:11:49,878 --> 00:12:06,035
Somebody once asked me or somebody once had this big doubt and said that it these things don't exist in the actual material world You know like it doesn't match with science as it were And that's where the confusion sometimes lies.

99
00:12:06,115 --> 00:12:16,527
The Buddha is not Talking about the external world as a scientific object He's talking about the internal world and how we experience the external world

100
00:12:17,586 --> 00:12:32,182
So when it comes to feeling, we can always go into feeling and discover the basic pieces or parts that make up that particular feeling.

101
00:12:32,764 --> 00:12:44,437
So if we take a very simple instance of just pain in the knees from sitting, first of all, you get this word pain, right?

102
00:12:45,258 --> 00:12:47,019
And you draw your attention to it.

103
00:12:47,692 --> 00:12:58,272
Now, in the process of vipassana, we also see the reaction that we've got to the pain.

104
00:12:59,033 --> 00:13:11,556
But what we're interested in at the moment is recognizing that the word pain is a concept, and it carries with it all our understanding about pain, all our personal experience about pain, what we've read about pain.

105
00:13:12,464 --> 00:13:20,835
So we're not actually experiencing the pain as pain, as a sensation, we're experiencing the concept that we're putting onto the pain.

106
00:13:21,335 --> 00:13:26,581
In order to experience the pain as pain, you have to go into the pain.

107
00:13:27,123 --> 00:13:34,412
And when you go into the pain, what you discover is things like heat, pressure, tightness, et cetera.

108
00:13:35,212 --> 00:13:39,879
And so there, we're beginning to deconstruct our physical nature.

109
00:13:40,600 --> 00:13:41,981
And in so doing,

110
00:13:42,147 --> 00:13:48,653
we're taking away this concept of pain and we're just there with the body as it gives us information.

111
00:13:49,995 --> 00:13:57,043
And that's where the Buddha is pointing to because right there we can see this process of impermanence much more clearly.

112
00:13:57,683 --> 00:14:02,149
These little sensations are continuously arising and passing away.

113
00:14:03,250 --> 00:14:09,015
But it also deconstructs for us this pain, right?

114
00:14:09,236 --> 00:14:11,479
So that's this process of

115
00:14:11,846 --> 00:14:40,993
um really understanding what he means by our physicality so it's the same with with our eating we're getting down to the actual experience of just the taste before we describe what food it is so you have to go right down to that physical base it's the same with hearing but it but the the other senses are much more difficult to grasp uh the the hearing and the seeing the seeing um

116
00:14:41,850 --> 00:14:43,693
There's a book called Just Seeing.

117
00:14:45,375 --> 00:14:48,139
I can't remember her name now.

118
00:14:49,621 --> 00:14:58,174
And obviously her insight was the way that what she was looking at broke up into all these different little pixels.

119
00:14:59,015 --> 00:15:09,731
And she talks about seeing the world like these pointillists, those artists that use little dots to create the image, trying to copy photography, I think.

120
00:15:10,572 --> 00:15:23,272
And just for a moment there the world split up into all these pixels you see and that's the information that's coming in on the retina When it comes to the to the ear Right there the ear drum.

121
00:15:23,591 --> 00:15:24,494
There's no sound.

122
00:15:24,854 --> 00:15:25,816
There's only pressure.

123
00:15:26,015 --> 00:15:37,653
It's the it's the pressure of the of the of the waves of the of the the pressure waves of air that are hitting the The drum in the ear so there's no sound in the universe.

124
00:15:37,673 --> 00:15:38,975
There's only these pressure waves

125
00:15:39,630 --> 00:16:01,280
But because we have this mechanism inside us to determine what the meaning of it is in terms of sound, from that point, from that point of just this pressure, these little drummings on top of the eardrum is taken into the mind and it's the mind that creates the sound.

126
00:16:03,443 --> 00:16:07,629
So this driving our attention

127
00:16:07,794 --> 00:16:36,451
know closer and closer to the physical base begins to deconstruct our experience you see and in deconstructing the experience and seeing it as a as a process one thing after another it just takes away that sense of of um something substantial some some entity some some wholeness right so that's that's all that all the business to do with the body

128
00:16:37,427 --> 00:16:43,356
Now, we can take that sort of investigation into feeling.

129
00:16:44,217 --> 00:16:58,740
Now, again, you've got feeling comes at the point where you're describing to yourself, where you determine to yourself whether something is pleasant or not, pleasant and unpleasant.

130
00:16:58,879 --> 00:17:02,284
That's how we immediately categorize feeling.

131
00:17:02,806 --> 00:17:05,490
And that's the dual world we live in, right?

132
00:17:05,509 --> 00:17:06,050
I mean, there's a,

133
00:17:06,554 --> 00:17:29,607
whole area of neutral feelings but if we really look into those neutral feelings you'll see they shade off into slightly unpleasant and slightly pleasant and that's that's the business of of the mind it's it's part of i suppose um just being able to survive in the world to know what's pleasant and what's not pleasant if you're a

134
00:17:29,790 --> 00:17:32,615
You know, if you're a hunter or something.

135
00:17:33,395 --> 00:17:46,134
So as soon as these basic sensations come in, they are immediately described by us to ourselves as being pleasant or unpleasant.

136
00:17:46,153 --> 00:17:48,116
And that's what the Buddha means by feeling.

137
00:17:48,616 --> 00:17:50,420
And these feelings are two types.

138
00:17:50,539 --> 00:17:56,407
There are the ones that are coming from the body itself and there's ones that are coming from the heart mind.

139
00:17:56,808 --> 00:17:59,071
So our emotional mood life.

140
00:18:00,335 --> 00:18:11,913
Now, just as we penetrated down into a physical feeling to discover that it's actually just made up of all these various different little sensations.

141
00:18:12,553 --> 00:18:14,496
So we do it with an emotion.

142
00:18:15,136 --> 00:18:18,923
So an emotion comes such as say anxiety.

143
00:18:19,743 --> 00:18:25,712
And by first of all, recognizing this is anxiety, this is anxiety.

144
00:18:25,953 --> 00:18:28,096
And then when you're steady, when you're,

145
00:18:28,279 --> 00:18:34,926
when you're feeling at ease with it, to actually go in and sink into it.

146
00:18:35,788 --> 00:18:41,513
Sink into it and to discover the sensations that make up this feeling of anxiety.

147
00:18:42,795 --> 00:18:46,739
And you may discover a lot of heat, a lot of agitation.

148
00:18:47,980 --> 00:18:54,507
And by doing that, you're deconstructing anxiety and beginning to realize actually, it's just a feeling.

149
00:18:55,954 --> 00:19:22,603
that somehow we take this feeling we give it a perspective by by putting a concept on it anxiety and then we identify with it we say i am anxious and that's how the suffering builds up but actually when we go down to the feeling of anxiety as a direct physical experience in the body well it's just a bit of heat and commotion that's all see and that

150
00:19:23,326 --> 00:19:31,499
And it's by deconstructing these emotions like that, that we lose a fear of them, that we begin to get a handle on them.

151
00:19:31,798 --> 00:19:37,728
And we recognize that anytime I feel like this, all I have to do is just sit with it, you see.

152
00:19:38,710 --> 00:19:47,042
And of course, there's the therapy because the heart then releases that energy outwardly as a feeling.

153
00:19:47,663 --> 00:19:49,906
And of course, it dies out.

154
00:19:51,288 --> 00:19:59,079
So these feelings, Buddha collects all that in one word, Vedana, just feeling.

155
00:19:59,780 --> 00:20:08,814
And so he doesn't make a distinction between, at the base, he doesn't make a distinction between mental and physical feelings.

156
00:20:09,675 --> 00:20:20,551
That's the next step up when he says, well, if you look again, you'll see that some sensations, some feelings, pleasant, unpleasant, are coming from the body and some are coming from

157
00:20:20,903 --> 00:20:22,263
the heart-mind.

158
00:20:22,984 --> 00:20:28,230
And when it comes from the body, sometimes you can't do anything about it.

159
00:20:28,371 --> 00:20:32,634
I mean, you know, physical pain, chronic pain and all that.

160
00:20:34,116 --> 00:20:49,272
And one of the techniques of, you know, getting used to chronic pain, if somebody has, you know, has such a thing to suffer, is to begin to deconstruct it and see it just as sensation.

161
00:20:49,979 --> 00:20:52,602
And then at least it's bearable, it becomes bearable.

162
00:20:52,801 --> 00:20:57,826
It can never become a pleasant experience, but at least it becomes bearable.

163
00:20:59,729 --> 00:21:07,057
When it comes to an emotional stuff, it's surprising how close sometimes it relates to physical feelings.

164
00:21:07,576 --> 00:21:13,663
I mean, heat and agitation, you know, these are actual physical feelings in the body.

165
00:21:14,785 --> 00:21:18,028
So this touching of the body and mind,

166
00:21:18,515 --> 00:21:23,820
is the place where we put our attention and that's where we see it as feeling.

167
00:21:24,601 --> 00:21:39,136
And in both cases, you can then penetrate it to find out the little bits of sensations that make up this so-called feeling, such as the heat and commotion or agitation that goes with anxiety.

168
00:21:40,999 --> 00:21:46,664
So that's the second candor, the second heap of experiences that we have.

169
00:21:47,067 --> 00:21:50,451
And this is how we explore them.

170
00:21:51,795 --> 00:21:59,306
Now, the third one is a little bit more, shall we say, difficult because it's to do with concepts.

171
00:21:59,386 --> 00:22:02,411
It's to do with perception and concepts.

172
00:22:03,413 --> 00:22:10,324
And what we have to recognize there is that when we have a particular experience,

173
00:22:10,894 --> 00:22:14,078
we create a photocopy of it in the mind.

174
00:22:14,858 --> 00:22:17,762
It can be a physical thing like eating an apple.

175
00:22:18,262 --> 00:22:21,066
It could be something that you see, a visual thing.

176
00:22:21,666 --> 00:22:25,230
It could be some intellectual understanding.

177
00:22:25,590 --> 00:22:30,757
But at some point, there's a copy of it in the mind, a little photocopy.

178
00:22:31,336 --> 00:22:32,378
That's your perception.

179
00:22:33,200 --> 00:22:38,184
And the more you have of that experience, this perception grows into a concept.

180
00:22:38,923 --> 00:22:46,073
So if for instance, I mean apples for instance, everybody's eaten an apple, and we have a concept of an apple.

181
00:22:46,093 --> 00:22:51,079
Now there are all types of apples, sweet apples, sour apples, cooking apples, small apples, big apples.

182
00:22:51,380 --> 00:22:55,285
There are lots of type of apples, but we definitely know they're not oranges.

183
00:22:56,086 --> 00:23:00,291
And that's what the conceptual, that's what a concept does for it.

184
00:23:00,832 --> 00:23:03,075
It allows us to categorize everything.

185
00:23:03,935 --> 00:23:05,218
But unfortunately,

186
00:23:05,653 --> 00:23:09,738
it also distorts what we're actually experiencing.

187
00:23:10,459 --> 00:23:18,286
So these concepts of an apple also come with a value judgment, what I like.

188
00:23:19,047 --> 00:23:20,888
So I like sweet apples.

189
00:23:21,288 --> 00:23:32,640
And if I chew into an apple that's sour or that has a certain bitterness to it or that it's too soft or whatever, I immediately get that reaction of not wanting it.

190
00:23:33,295 --> 00:23:48,273
But if I'd never tasted an apple before, and this was the first apple I had, which had a little bit of bitterness and a little bit of softness, I'd say, well, this is an amazing fruit.

191
00:23:49,615 --> 00:23:53,720
And you would build up your concept from there about apples and what you like.

192
00:23:54,741 --> 00:23:57,765
So our concepts are quite constricting.

193
00:23:58,605 --> 00:24:02,391
And part of our process is to

194
00:24:02,624 --> 00:24:08,430
is to get beyond concepts, beyond concepts, and to get to a point of no preference.

195
00:24:09,230 --> 00:24:19,140
I mean, that's one of the signs of liberation that we don't worry about whether the apple is soft or hard, bitter or sweet, you just eat the damn thing.

196
00:24:20,240 --> 00:24:30,471
So concepts are really one of our biggest enemies when it comes to the process of liberation.

197
00:24:30,990 --> 00:24:35,660
You know, you can have even a concept of nibbana.

198
00:24:35,680 --> 00:24:39,768
You read about it and there's this idea about it being blissful.

199
00:24:39,788 --> 00:24:43,355
You'll often hear the bliss of nibbana.

200
00:24:43,375 --> 00:24:49,226
And so we immediately think that it must be some, you know, amazing emotional experience.

201
00:24:49,928 --> 00:24:51,210
But there's no emotions in nibbana.

202
00:24:52,085 --> 00:25:01,858
So when somebody says to, you know, Sariputta, how is it you talk about the bliss of Nibbana when there's no emotions, there's no moods, there's nothing there?

203
00:25:01,878 --> 00:25:05,343
He says, well, it's the very absence of emotions and moods.

204
00:25:05,383 --> 00:25:07,506
That is the bliss of Nibbana.

205
00:25:08,086 --> 00:25:09,409
Try to get your head around that one.

206
00:25:09,849 --> 00:25:19,542
So as soon as we have some sort of concept, it's immediately limiting and distorting by the very nature of concepts.

207
00:25:20,214 --> 00:25:31,788
And of course, when these concepts become great, big, grand things like freedom, democracy, well, I mean, you know, it just becomes personal ideas.

208
00:25:33,030 --> 00:25:41,981
And our process of meditation is really, when we're sitting in vipassana, is to really stop all that business.

209
00:25:42,362 --> 00:25:46,027
And that's one of the purposes, remember, of using a single word.

210
00:25:46,426 --> 00:25:49,310
Because what that word does, at least it draws us.

211
00:25:49,527 --> 00:25:54,134
this intellect down to a very simple concrete concept.

212
00:25:54,153 --> 00:25:57,818
So you're lifting or moving or pushing or pulling.

213
00:25:57,838 --> 00:26:07,613
These are still concepts, these are still concepts, but at least it's not creating a process of thinking about something.

214
00:26:09,134 --> 00:26:11,739
And we're always looking through the word, right?

215
00:26:11,759 --> 00:26:14,722
The word isn't meant to be right in front of us.

216
00:26:15,964 --> 00:26:19,450
Some people who begin noting or use noting

217
00:26:19,970 --> 00:26:28,098
at first, find that they can't actually get to the feeling of things because the word is so tight up against them.

218
00:26:29,140 --> 00:26:31,722
It's like a barrier to actual feeling something.

219
00:26:32,503 --> 00:26:43,355
And what this tells a person is how this awareness, this ability to feel, to directly experience is being locked into a concept.

220
00:26:44,156 --> 00:26:45,218
And it's only by

221
00:26:45,383 --> 00:27:04,201
So we say looking through the word or around the word or under the word or finding some way of, as it were, letting the word go and actually getting down to the feeling of it, that this awareness, this intuitive awareness, liberates itself from conceptual thinking.

222
00:27:05,241 --> 00:27:07,765
And that's really very much part of our process.

223
00:27:09,006 --> 00:27:13,230
And that doesn't mean to say you can then forget all about concepts, not at all.

224
00:27:13,597 --> 00:27:15,642
you use them when you have to use them.

225
00:27:15,961 --> 00:27:25,038
But in order to begin to see the world as it really is, we have to see the limitation of these concepts.

226
00:27:26,660 --> 00:27:36,877
I mean, just on a grand scale, you can see that people in the East, I'm thinking of places like China, Japan, etc.

227
00:27:37,338 --> 00:27:38,019
People there

228
00:27:38,269 --> 00:27:41,874
have a very different concept of society.

229
00:27:42,355 --> 00:27:52,688
They have a, you know, they have a feel for a community in a way that the Westerner, because of this accent upon the the individual, doesn't have.

230
00:27:53,388 --> 00:27:56,311
So for us, our rights are so important.

231
00:27:56,332 --> 00:27:57,993
You know, we jump up and down.

232
00:27:58,074 --> 00:27:59,316
It's my right, it's my right.

233
00:28:00,426 --> 00:28:09,559
Whereas for somebody who sees themselves as part of a community, it's much more in a sense of connection, a sense of beauty to others.

234
00:28:10,402 --> 00:28:18,693
So, you know, it's a real alive present day separation because of this concept we have of who we are.

235
00:28:19,375 --> 00:28:25,624
As a Westerner, I think of myself as an individual pod and I can do my own thing in my own way in my own time.

236
00:28:25,974 --> 00:28:30,942
And if I were an Easterner, I'd be thinking much more, well, what are the others doing?

237
00:28:31,402 --> 00:28:32,624
You know, how can I work with them?

238
00:28:33,265 --> 00:28:41,316
So you can see that these concepts that we have of ourselves are by definition limiting.

239
00:28:41,655 --> 00:28:48,065
So for the Easterner, you know, the idea of being your own agent is difficult.

240
00:28:48,204 --> 00:28:55,914
And that's why I presume, this is my own little understanding, why they're much more happy with authoritarian regimes.

241
00:28:57,430 --> 00:28:58,391
That's just by the sign.

242
00:28:58,791 --> 00:29:05,720
So you can see that conceptual thinking is quite a problem for us.

243
00:29:05,740 --> 00:29:08,202
And we have to really see it.

244
00:29:08,423 --> 00:29:24,383
And the greatest concept, of course, that really is at the root of everything is this concept of a self, this concept of that idea of being a me, an individual, whole, entire person.

245
00:29:27,011 --> 00:29:33,846
the, shall we say, the basis of everything that we build up into being a person.

246
00:29:34,709 --> 00:29:45,814
So this is undermined by really, you know, understanding ourselves as a collection of these different heaps, these different aggregates.

247
00:29:46,334 --> 00:29:59,088
And it's not just an intellectual process, remember, it begins there, but you actually have to see it, you have to feel it, you have to see that a sensation, that an emotion is just sensations, that's all it is.

248
00:29:59,849 --> 00:30:13,506
And that thinking, you don't have to believe a thought, you don't have to describe yourself by a particular set of concepts, you see, being able to step outside them.

249
00:30:14,599 --> 00:30:19,425
So that's this whole business of perception and conceptualization.

250
00:30:19,727 --> 00:30:21,808
And remember, this also includes memory.

251
00:30:23,431 --> 00:30:33,243
Often, my teacher once said, he said, there are these five aggregates, and he went through the five aggregates, and then he said, and there's memory.

252
00:30:33,403 --> 00:30:34,746
The Buddha forgot memory.

253
00:30:36,048 --> 00:30:38,931
It was like everybody's jaw dropped, you know.

254
00:30:39,692 --> 00:30:40,894
And the reason why...

255
00:30:41,346 --> 00:30:47,977
Why the Buddha doesn't talk about memory as such is because our memories are, shall we say, hidden from us.

256
00:30:48,336 --> 00:31:00,994
What we're working with moment after moment are these concepts and these ideas, these feelings, et cetera, et cetera, that arise in the present moment.

257
00:31:01,015 --> 00:31:04,079
So the Buddha is not denying memory.

258
00:31:04,420 --> 00:31:07,084
It's just that, you know,

259
00:31:07,569 --> 00:31:12,679
As soon as you remember something, it becomes something that's actual.

260
00:31:12,699 --> 00:31:17,928
But all the past is hidden to us unless it comes into our consciousness.

261
00:31:18,088 --> 00:31:26,363
So in terms of the Buddha's understanding, it's not, shall we say, pertinent to seeing ourselves as we really are.

262
00:31:28,606 --> 00:31:31,873
And then the fourth one is Sankara.

263
00:31:32,258 --> 00:31:34,545
Those things that are compounded.

264
00:31:35,366 --> 00:31:42,689
I mean, people try to translate it in some ways like volitional conditionings or concoctions.

265
00:31:42,849 --> 00:31:45,036
One writer called them concoctions.

266
00:31:45,369 --> 00:31:48,134
But I think it's much easier for us to see them as habits.

267
00:31:48,354 --> 00:31:49,836
These are our habits.

268
00:31:50,296 --> 00:31:54,501
And the thing about a habit is that it's driven by will.

269
00:31:55,262 --> 00:32:02,051
So the Buddha is quite clear that an action and the will are the same thing.

270
00:32:02,573 --> 00:32:13,487
And that's why, you know, when we are having a meal, that's the time to really make that distinction between a desire, which is only potential,

271
00:32:13,702 --> 00:32:17,406
And then it's suddenly empowered by an act of will.

272
00:32:17,527 --> 00:32:24,213
A decision is made and the power goes into that desire and it begins to manifest.

273
00:32:24,233 --> 00:32:33,763
Now, the process is that with an action, so you've performed an action and there's consequences, of course.

274
00:32:33,784 --> 00:32:34,584
That's the karma.

275
00:32:34,604 --> 00:32:35,685
We'll come to that in a minute.

276
00:32:36,807 --> 00:32:41,971
But once you produce an action and you repeat an action, then you're building up a habit.

277
00:32:43,251 --> 00:32:48,659
And when you put all these habits together, that's our personality, that's our character.

278
00:32:49,279 --> 00:32:54,046
And once that's set, you know, your destiny is right ahead of you.

279
00:32:54,705 --> 00:33:10,946
And it's only by reflecting upon our habits and beginning to see that some of them are sort of taking us to the cliff edge, and some of them are taking us up to the mountain, up the Nirvanic mountain, that you begin to try and get rid of some and increase the others.

280
00:33:11,669 --> 00:33:19,299
So these habits are, shall we say, a collection of things that we ourselves have created.

281
00:33:20,922 --> 00:33:25,067
We've done it from our sense of wisdom or lack of wisdom.

282
00:33:26,009 --> 00:33:27,731
We've empowered these desires.

283
00:33:28,752 --> 00:33:32,117
This is what we have created within ourselves.

284
00:33:32,557 --> 00:33:34,580
My habits are my creation.

285
00:33:35,603 --> 00:33:39,448
Now, it might have been done because of somebody's advice.

286
00:33:39,627 --> 00:33:40,950
It might have been done because

287
00:33:41,250 --> 00:33:43,294
somebody told me to do it.

288
00:33:43,713 --> 00:33:44,694
It doesn't really matter.

289
00:33:45,797 --> 00:33:53,426
Eventually, the process is internal, and I've made the decision, and I've created the habit.

290
00:33:54,647 --> 00:33:59,413
And in this sense, you begin to understand that nobody can actually make you suffer.

291
00:34:00,635 --> 00:34:01,717
Nobody can make you suffer.

292
00:34:02,337 --> 00:34:04,240
All the suffering is made by us.

293
00:34:05,501 --> 00:34:10,228
These are our habits, our mental states, and I've created them.

294
00:34:11,152 --> 00:34:17,809
And once we recognize that, then we also begin to realize that just as we've created them, we can uncreate them.

295
00:34:17,829 --> 00:34:22,360
And that's part of the therapy of our process when we sit in meditation.

296
00:34:22,862 --> 00:34:28,757
Because when you sit with a habit which is causing you problems,

297
00:34:28,989 --> 00:34:31,653
I don't know, something like a quick temper.

298
00:34:32,175 --> 00:34:44,894
See, so by sitting with that feeling of anger and allowing it to evaporate, right, to release itself, we're undermining the habit of anger.

299
00:34:44,914 --> 00:34:50,523
Now, anger itself is, shall we say, like a balloon inside our psyche.

300
00:34:51,304 --> 00:34:54,228
And it is not actually attached to an object.

301
00:34:54,849 --> 00:34:55,891
This is a funny thing.

302
00:34:56,057 --> 00:35:01,764
So for instance, it's not that somebody standing on my toe is causing the anger.

303
00:35:02,766 --> 00:35:08,474
It's my reaction to somebody standing on my toe, which is causing the anger to arise.

304
00:35:10,516 --> 00:35:20,269
So in other words, these mental states that we have, these habits, these emotional habits that we have, don't actually have an object.

305
00:35:20,389 --> 00:35:24,494
They are a way of reacting to something.

306
00:35:25,032 --> 00:35:50,010
because of that because the outer world and other people are not the direct cause of my unwholesome mental states That's because because of that I can actually heal myself If other people caused me suffering then the only way to achieve Nirvana is to get rid of all these other people But that's not

307
00:35:50,902 --> 00:35:53,746
But that isn't the way that the Buddha pointed.

308
00:35:53,766 --> 00:35:56,650
He said, no, the problem is us internally.

309
00:35:58,092 --> 00:36:11,128
So these sankharas, these habits, our job is to, you know, get to allow these unwholesome ones to evaporate and to build up the ones that are beautiful.

310
00:36:12,150 --> 00:36:13,771
And we can do that, right?

311
00:36:13,791 --> 00:36:14,532
We can do that.

312
00:36:14,552 --> 00:36:18,798
In the sitting, we're tending to allow the more...

313
00:36:19,032 --> 00:36:30,686
unfortunate mental stage to evaporate, but then in our daily lives, that's when we can build up our goodness, our goodness power, punya.

314
00:36:31,527 --> 00:36:37,896
Sometimes that's translated as merit, but it's much better to think of it as goodness power.

315
00:36:37,916 --> 00:36:41,960
So that's where this transition comes from vipassana into daily life.

316
00:36:43,103 --> 00:36:45,545
That's where the Eightfold Path comes in.

317
00:36:45,914 --> 00:37:13,356
you know right speech right action right livelihood so it's through action in the world that we can actually change these habits also in fact that's the most powerful place to do it because it's only when we come up against things that make us anxious depressed angry and so on so that that we can actually work with it right there as it were as it takes place and undermine the uh

318
00:37:13,639 --> 00:37:16,565
the energy that we put in reinforcing those states.

319
00:37:17,565 --> 00:37:27,101
So these sankaras include that sense of desire, the wrong desire, the reactions that we have to things.

320
00:37:29,105 --> 00:37:39,882
And it's seeing the reaction and allowing the reaction to dissipate and allowing the original mental state to arise and evaporate

321
00:37:40,166 --> 00:37:45,210
That is the process of healing, of healing the heart with therapy.

322
00:37:46,411 --> 00:37:49,355
And as I say, it definitely happens when you're sitting.

323
00:37:49,815 --> 00:37:56,320
And if we've got this awareness, this mindfulness in daily life, it'll also happen just in ordinary daily life.

324
00:37:57,762 --> 00:38:03,327
Because you're aware, like for instance, you talk to somebody and you can feel a little bit of irritation coming, you know.

325
00:38:04,068 --> 00:38:09,853
So that awareness has to be both on the person who's talking, but also inwardly.

326
00:38:10,289 --> 00:38:14,014
And when you see this irritation rising, you see, you don't join in.

327
00:38:14,375 --> 00:38:17,280
You just let it burn a little bit.

328
00:38:17,300 --> 00:38:19,943
You put your attention on what the person is saying.

329
00:38:20,724 --> 00:38:25,152
Whereas often what we do is we immediately identify with this.

330
00:38:25,492 --> 00:38:27,175
I'm right and that person's wrong.

331
00:38:27,596 --> 00:38:30,320
And before you know it, it's all shouting.

332
00:38:31,340 --> 00:38:37,731
So the sankharas are all the habits that we have, that we've created ourselves,

333
00:38:37,913 --> 00:38:58,469
and that this is where our creativity actually lies, that we can move away from all those habits that we find unwholesome and which are a pest to other people and move towards habits which make us inwardly happy and delightful to other people.

334
00:39:00,188 --> 00:39:02,710
And then finally, there's this consciousness, right?

335
00:39:02,731 --> 00:39:07,596
And we've already touched upon that with Narcissus looking into the pond.

336
00:39:08,336 --> 00:39:10,659
Everything has to arise on that consciousness.

337
00:39:11,300 --> 00:39:23,713
Now, unfortunately, the Buddha, you know, like he's had this massive breakthrough and the language, he can't hold it in the language.

338
00:39:23,733 --> 00:39:28,237
You know, he can't make up a word to actually express things.

339
00:39:28,893 --> 00:39:32,155
So he's always playing around with words.

340
00:39:32,577 --> 00:39:39,204
Words depend upon the situation that he's describing.

341
00:39:39,985 --> 00:39:57,043
And so often he'll talk about vijnana, consciousness, as something that discriminates, which actually is the effect of these sankharas, this ability to understand on the screen of consciousness.

342
00:39:57,731 --> 00:40:17,871
But when we go down to that root position, which the contact, that place of contact of consciousness with the physical body, consciousness with emotions, consciousness with thought, when we get down to that point, there's always an object, the internal object or the external object.

343
00:40:18,231 --> 00:40:19,472
There's always a sense base.

344
00:40:19,893 --> 00:40:22,275
The sixth sense, remember, is the mind itself.

345
00:40:22,434 --> 00:40:27,300
It's the mind that senses emotions and images and all that.

346
00:40:27,769 --> 00:40:29,271
and consciousness.

347
00:40:29,612 --> 00:40:32,454
So this consciousness turns out to be just a screen.

348
00:40:33,594 --> 00:40:44,865
And the whole position of vipassana is to step, as it were, backwards outside the screen.

349
00:40:45,226 --> 00:40:54,034
But there's always that sense of a self, which is awareness itself actually catching its own sense of presence on that screen.

350
00:40:54,715 --> 00:40:56,697
And that's the first object that we make.

351
00:40:57,132 --> 00:40:59,135
That's the first concept we have.

352
00:40:59,978 --> 00:41:04,728
And it's breaking through that, that is, you know, the point of liberation.

353
00:41:05,110 --> 00:41:15,192
And then to be able to sustain that separation in ordinary daily life, that of course is the sign of someone who's fully liberated.

354
00:41:16,639 --> 00:41:21,443
So finally, what then is our karma?

355
00:41:21,905 --> 00:41:31,773
You know, when you look at all this, when we talk about karma, when we talk about, you know, what is it that we are responsible for?

356
00:41:31,893 --> 00:41:33,554
What is the consequences?

357
00:41:34,135 --> 00:41:38,358
It actually is confined to what we will.

358
00:41:39,159 --> 00:41:44,925
So it wouldn't be right to think, say, this body is my personal karma.

359
00:41:45,344 --> 00:41:53,355
You know, this body is a construction that's arisen out of generations of people.

360
00:41:54,115 --> 00:41:56,099
And, you know, I didn't choose it.

361
00:41:56,219 --> 00:41:58,581
I would have preferred, you know, a better body.

362
00:42:00,784 --> 00:42:01,726
But this one's okay.

363
00:42:01,927 --> 00:42:02,827
You know, I'm not complaining.

364
00:42:03,108 --> 00:42:03,289
Oh, no.

365
00:42:03,748 --> 00:42:06,773
So this one's been healthy, et cetera, et cetera.

366
00:42:06,793 --> 00:42:08,655
So I'm definitely not complaining.

367
00:42:09,396 --> 00:42:11,340
But the body, of course, has been given to me.

368
00:42:11,360 --> 00:42:13,021
I find myself in a body.

369
00:42:13,576 --> 00:42:20,987
The society I am born into with all its language and its concepts and its art and all that is all the given.

370
00:42:22,230 --> 00:42:27,016
That is also not my personal karma.

371
00:42:27,657 --> 00:42:40,478
If I happen to, so we say, cross a road and get knocked over by a car, even if I'm not seriously injured, just bumped, you might say, we can't say that's my personal karma.

372
00:42:40,744 --> 00:43:01,775
Personal karma, the karma which is to do with liberation, is this process of purifying the heart of its unwholesome conditionings and beginning to see where the delusion, the fundamental delusion rises, which is this sense of self.

373
00:43:02,856 --> 00:43:08,085
So if we go backwards and recognize that what's happening is,

374
00:43:08,420 --> 00:43:18,253
this awareness, this intuitive awareness, sees itself, gets a feeling for itself, a sense of presence on that screen of consciousness.

375
00:43:19,175 --> 00:43:25,043
And it sees on that screen of consciousness the world which the body, heart and mind are creating.

376
00:43:25,643 --> 00:43:30,351
And it moves into that world with the idea of becoming happy.

377
00:43:31,032 --> 00:43:34,657
Hence, it has to acquire things, right?

378
00:43:34,697 --> 00:43:37,701
The whole position of acquisition is to make us safe,

379
00:43:38,001 --> 00:44:03,621
to make us happy the more you have the better we think we're going to be you know it's much better to have a couple of million in the bank than just a couple of you know than 10 pounds so we're always trying to accumulate things once we've accumulated uh we find that other people want what we have and therefore you have to defend and you have to protect and that's the aversion that's and and when when the

380
00:44:03,887 --> 00:44:11,217
when the enemy is a bit too big, you run for it, so there's your fear, so there's your reaction of fight and flight.

381
00:44:11,938 --> 00:44:23,050
And these are our basic, unwholesome motivations that run through from that initial delusion.

382
00:44:23,911 --> 00:44:32,342
So, it's by doing the opposite, it's by renouncing ownership of things, it's by giving

383
00:44:32,608 --> 00:44:38,976
that we begin to undo the delusion, right?

384
00:44:38,996 --> 00:44:42,021
So that's the whole process of the Eightfold Path.

385
00:44:43,023 --> 00:44:48,168
And undoing the delusion, of course, we go right back to this sense of self.

386
00:44:48,650 --> 00:45:02,547
And that's when, at some point, there is this opening of the heart and recognition of this community, this communion that we have with not only people, but all beings.

387
00:45:03,202 --> 00:45:11,070
And that's when you might say the path of love takes us towards the end of this very tight sense of me.

388
00:45:12,032 --> 00:45:17,518
And that leads us to a deeper concept about this awareness.

389
00:45:18,378 --> 00:45:27,608
But ultimately, through the process of insight, there comes this realization of the uniqueness of this intuitive awareness.

390
00:45:27,976 --> 00:45:40,550
And this is what the Buddha is pointing to when he talks about there is an unborn, undying, uncreated, unconditioned, and that's it, that's the statement.

391
00:45:40,570 --> 00:45:49,460
He makes other statements too, such as there is a dimension, ayatana, there is a dimension.

392
00:45:49,795 --> 00:45:52,798
which doesn't have any of the other dimensions in it.

393
00:45:53,480 --> 00:45:59,427
Now the word iatana refers to the dimensions of each of the sense spaces.

394
00:46:00,248 --> 00:46:02,090
So the sense spaces can't be mixed.

395
00:46:02,311 --> 00:46:05,034
You can't hear through your nose, even if you try.

396
00:46:05,835 --> 00:46:09,659
So these are different dimensions of experience.

397
00:46:10,260 --> 00:46:19,632
And he says that there is a dimension where none of these dimensions can be found, where there's no hearing, no seeing, et cetera, et cetera.

398
00:46:19,916 --> 00:46:28,690
There's many times that he points to something which is beyond transcendent of the world that we're actually experiencing.

399
00:46:28,710 --> 00:46:37,744
So our process is through vipassana to begin to see these three characteristics.

400
00:46:38,085 --> 00:46:44,675
We haven't talked so much about this reaction, which is also part of that sankara business of the habits.

401
00:46:44,976 --> 00:46:56,028
we pointed to it in terms of acquiring of acquisition, greed, avarice and so on and the opposite of fight and flight.

402
00:46:56,188 --> 00:46:58,731
That's all in that habitual thing.

403
00:46:58,751 --> 00:47:01,034
That's all part of our true karma.

404
00:47:02,034 --> 00:47:09,043
So the process of vipassana is partly to do with purifying that which happens quite naturally and

405
00:47:09,563 --> 00:47:15,271
But it's also, or should we say, more pertinent in that we're actually seeing the process of desire.

406
00:47:15,771 --> 00:47:17,755
We're seeing the process of impermanence.

407
00:47:18,195 --> 00:47:27,128
And we're seeing that, you know, from that position of the observer, that things arise of their own accord, that they don't have a possessor.

408
00:47:27,728 --> 00:47:31,074
They just happen through habitual practice.

409
00:47:31,775 --> 00:47:33,818
So these are your three characteristics.

410
00:47:34,619 --> 00:47:37,983
And in ordinary daily life, it's this process of,

411
00:47:38,335 --> 00:47:50,284
you know, undoing that sort of selfishness, that sort of constant looking after me as opposed to others, that opening of the heart to other people.

412
00:47:51,065 --> 00:47:56,931
And that undermines the self as a concept, as an emotional concept.

413
00:47:57,851 --> 00:48:07,599
And that's the process through love, compassion, sympathetic joy, that undermines the idea, the notion of a self.

414
00:48:08,221 --> 00:48:12,144
And eventually, of course, there is that liberation.

415
00:48:12,425 --> 00:48:19,331
The liberation is from all these wrong concepts, from all these wrong habits.

416
00:48:19,351 --> 00:48:20,472
That's what the liberation is.

417
00:48:24,918 --> 00:48:25,438
Very good.

418
00:48:25,978 --> 00:48:31,965
So I hope that's been of some, you know, use.

419
00:48:32,045 --> 00:48:35,307
It's not caused even further confusion.

420
00:48:35,608 --> 00:48:41,028
and that you will, by your effort, liberate yourself sooner rather than later.

